---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const books = [
  { slug: 'in-his-image',              title: 'In His Image' },
  { slug: 'the-purpose-driven-life',   title: 'The Purpose Driven Life' },
  { slug: 'the-power-of-a-humble-life', title: 'The Power of a Humble Life' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Grow in Wisdom — Personal Takeaways"
  description="Personal takeaways from the Grow in Wisdom shelf: a weekly character formation plan built around eight traits — Loving, Humble, Self-Controlled, Hopeful, Wise, Joyful, Peaceful, Courageous."
>
  <a class="overlay-back" href="/">&#8592; Back to Bookshelf</a>
  <a class="overlay-close" href="/" aria-label="Close">&times;</a>

  <div class="takeaways-content">
    <span class="takeaways-tag">Grow in Wisdom</span>
    <h1 class="takeaways-title">Grow in Wisdom</h1>
    <p class="takeaways-author" style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Personal Takeaways</p>

    <div style="display:flex; gap:0.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap; margin-bottom:2rem;">
      {books.map((b) => (
        <a href={`/books/${b.slug}/`} class="overlay-takeaways-btn" style="font-size:0.78rem; padding:0.35rem 0.9rem;">
          {b.title}
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>

    <div class="tk-section" id="giw-ethical-will" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="tk-section-title">The Ethical Will</div>
      <p style="font-family:'EB Garamond',serif;font-size:.95rem;color:#5E554B;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:1rem">Most people spend their lives asking <em>what should I do next?</em> Wilkin's correction in <em>In His Image</em> is blunt: the better question is <em>who should I be?</em> Warren goes further — your character is the only thing you carry into eternity; everything else gets left behind. The failure mode isn't laziness. It's that most people never force themselves to answer the question while they still can. They accumulate experiences, relationships, and opinions without ever distilling them into a settled conviction about what their life is for. An ethical will does what journaling and goal-setting can't: it makes you write your life in the past tense before it's over. When you name your three ingredients — a passion to live for, people to love, and a God to live toward — you stop drifting and start building toward something specific. The document externalizes your values so they can hold you accountable. It removes the ambiguity that lets lesser priorities sneak in. It turns character formation from a vague aspiration into a defined target. I wrote mine at twenty. I still read it. Not every person with good intentions becomes the person they hoped to be — but almost every person who writes it down does.</p>
      <a class="go-deeper-btn" href="/grow-in-wisdom/takeaways-eulogy-letter/">Read the Full Eulogy Letter &rarr;</a>
    </div>

    <div class="tk-section" id="giw-character-plan" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="tk-section-title">Weekly Character Plan</div>
      <p style="font-family:'EB Garamond',serif;font-size:.95rem;color:#5E554B;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:1rem">Wilkin argued that the most important work of a Christian is being conformed to the image of Christ. Character formation doesn't happen by accident or through good intentions. It requires honest self-examination on a regular cadence. This plan is structured around eight character traits — Loving, Humble, Self-Controlled, Hopeful, Wise, Joyful, Peaceful, and Courageous — each with a four-step reflection rhythm (Recall, Examine, Apply, Pray).</p>
      <p style="font-family:'EB Garamond',serif;font-size:.95rem;color:#5E554B;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:1rem">Use the button below to open the full 8-trait weekly schedule and reflection prompts.</p>
      <a class="go-deeper-btn" href="/grow-in-wisdom/takeaways-character-plan/">See Full Weekly Character Plan &rarr;</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  html { scroll-behavior: smooth; }
</style>
